You’re circling around a real biological phenomenon, but the details are a little different than the idea that pain literally “turns into pleasure.”

What actually happens biologically

When mammals experience extreme stress or injury, the body can release chemicals that dampen pain or create euphoria so the animal can keep functioning long enough to escape danger.

Two important systems are involved:
	•	Endorphins – natural opioid-like molecules that reduce pain and can produce calm or mild euphoria.
	•	Adrenaline / stress hormones – increase alertness and temporarily suppress pain perception.

This phenomenon is often called Stress‑induced analgesia.

For example:
	•	A prey animal caught by a predator may stop struggling and appear calm.
	•	Humans in accidents sometimes report feeling little or no pain initially, even with serious injuries.

The body is basically saying:

“Survival first. Pain later.”

