Why it can feel like “pain becomes pleasure”

Endorphins interact with the same receptors as opioid drugs, so when they surge the experience can include:
	•	pain reduction
	•	emotional numbness
	•	sometimes a sense of warmth or relief

That can make it seem like pain flips into pleasure, but what’s really happening is the nervous system turning down the pain signal and stabilizing the mind under extreme stress.

⸻

The “thinking makes it so” part

Your brain also plays a role. Expectation, belief, and focus can change pain perception through mechanisms like the Placebo Effect and top-down pain modulation from the brain.

Examples:
	•	Athletes finishing a race on an injured leg
	•	Soldiers not noticing wounds until after combat
	•	Meditation changing how pain is experienced

The signal is partly physical, partly interpreted by the brain.

⸻

A systems way to think about it

Pain and pleasure are not opposites; they’re signals in the same regulatory loop.

damage → pain signal → survival response → recovery → relief/pleasure

That “relief” stage is where the brain often releases rewarding chemicals, reinforcing survival behaviors.

So the system looks like:

Pain = warning
Relief = reward

Both are feedback mechanisms keeping the organism alive.

